## The Core Idea

Backtracking is **controlled brute force**. You build a solution one piece at a time, and the moment a path cannot possibly lead to a valid answer, you **undo the last choice and try a different one**.

The name comes from exactly that — you go forward, hit a dead end, then backtrack to where you were and try again.

---

## The Mental Model

Think of a maze:

```
Start
  ↓
Choice A → Choice A1 → dead end → backtrack
         → Choice A2 → dead end → backtrack
Choice B → Choice B1 → dead end → backtrack
         → Choice B2 → SOLUTION ✓
```

You never reset to the beginning. You only undo the **last decision** and try the next option from that same point.

---

## The Generic Template — Memorise This

Every backtracking problem uses this exact shape:

```java
void backtrack(/* current state */, /* choices available */, List<...> result) {

    // BASE CASE — did we reach a complete solution?
    if (solutionIsComplete()) {
        result.add(/* copy of current solution */);
        return;
    }

    // EXPLORE — try every available choice
    for (choice : availableChoices) {

        // 1. MAKE the choice
        makeChoice(choice);

        // 2. RECURSE — go deeper with this choice made
        backtrack(newState, remainingChoices, result);

        // 3. UNDO the choice — backtrack
        undoChoice(choice);
    }
}
```

The three lines inside the loop — make, recurse, undo — are the heartbeat of every backtracking solution. You will write them hundreds of times.

