## The Three Patterns Side by Side

```
PERMUTATIONS          SUBSETS               CONSTRAINED
all orderings         all combinations      valid only

used[] array          start index           if condition
to avoid reuse        to avoid repeats      before recursing

add at BASE CASE      add at EVERY NODE     add at BASE CASE
(when full)           (immediately)         (when full)
```

---

## Time Complexity — Be Ready to Say This

```
Permutations  → O(n × n!)   — n! permutations, each takes O(n) to copy
Subsets       → O(n × 2ⁿ)   — 2ⁿ subsets, each takes O(n) to copy
Parentheses   → O(4ⁿ / √n)  — Catalan number, just say "exponential"
```

In interviews just say: "backtracking is exponential time because we explore all possibilities, but pruning cuts branches early so it is faster in practice."

---

## The Four Questions to Ask Before Writing Any Backtracking Solution

```
1. What is one "choice" at each step?
   → permutations: which character to place next
   → subsets: include this character or not

2. What is the base case?
   → permutations: current length == s.length()
   → subsets: no more characters to consider

3. What constraint prunes invalid paths?
   → permutations: skip used characters
   → parentheses: never add ')' if close >= open

4. Do I need a copy when I add to result?
   → StringBuilder: yes — current.toString()
   → primitive: no — add directly
```

---

## The One Rule to Never Forget

> Every `make choice` must have an exact matching `undo choice` after the recursive call. If you make and do not undo, the state is corrupted for every other branch. Make and undo are always a pair.

```java
current.append(c);              // make
backtrack(...);                 // recurse
current.deleteCharAt(...);      // undo ← must always exist
```

---

## Your Practice Checklist

Work these in order — same template, increasing constraint complexity:

1. All permutations of a string — pure backtracking, no constraints
2. All subsets of a string — teaches the start index pattern
3. Generate valid parentheses — introduces pruning with constraints
4. Letter combinations of a phone number — maps digits to letters, same template
5. Word search in a grid — backtracking on a 2D grid, adds visited tracking

Once you can write permutations and subsets from memory, the template is locked in. Every other backtracking problem is just a variation of what the choices are and what the constraints are.